# UDS Site Changelog

Whenever you modify ANY file in `uds-docs/`, you MUST perform these three steps before completing the task:

## 1. Bump the SITE version

**Run `bash uds-docs/bump-site.sh`** — this handles everything:
- Gets today's date from the system `date` command (NEVER guess)
- Increments N if same day, resets to `.1` if new day
- Updates all 3 locations: index.html display, index.html inline SITE_VERSION, version.txt

NEVER manually edit the version string. ALWAYS use the script.

## 2. Add a SITE_CHANGELOG entry

After the repo restructure, the SITE changelog lives at
`uds-docs/docs/data/site-changelog.js` (no longer inside `app.js`). Find
the `SITE_CHANGELOG` array and **append** a new entry for the current SITE
version (newest entries go LAST in the array — the renderer reverses for
display):

```javascript
{
  version: 'SITE YYYY.MM.DD.N',   // matches the version in index.html
  date: 'YYYY-MM-DD',
  changes: [
    { type: 'added|changed|fixed|removed', text: 'Description of what changed' }
  ]
}
```

- If you're making multiple changes in one session, batch them into a single version entry
- If an entry for the current version already exists, append to its `changes` array
- Types: `added` (new feature/page), `changed` (modification), `fixed` (bug fix), `removed` (deletion)

## 3. Cache busting

Three things to update:

### a. Query params on script/link tags in `index.html`:
- `<link rel="stylesheet" href="./uds/uds.css?v=N" />` — bump if any CSS changed
- `<script src="./uds/uds.js?v=N"></script>` — bump if any JS changed
- `<script type="module" src="./docs/app.js?v=N"></script>` — bump if `docs/app.js` (or anything it imports) changed
- `<script type="module" src="./docs/modules/demo-builder/index.js?v=N"></script>` — bump if any Demo Builder module changed
- `<link rel="stylesheet" href="./docs/site.css?v=N" />` — bump if `docs/site.css` changed

Only bump the ones where the underlying file actually changed.

### b. Update `version.txt`:
Write the new SITE version number (just the `YYYY.MM.DD.N` part, no `SITE` prefix) to `uds-docs/version.txt`. This file is fetched on every page load to trigger auto-reload when a new version is deployed.

### c. Update the inline SITE_VERSION in `index.html`:
Find the `var SITE_VERSION = '...'` string in the inline `<script>` block in `<head>` and update it to match the new version.

## 4. Voice and length

SITE_CHANGELOG entries appear on the live Changelog page. They are read
by humans, not by audits. Write them the way the early entries did —
short, descriptive, designer-readable.

### Audience

The reader is a senior product designer. Technically literate — they
understand tokens, components, file structure, the difference between a
CSS class and a JS function. They are not asking to be talked down to.
They are also not reading the changelog to debug code; they are reading
it to know what shipped.

### Test for whether to use a technical term

Use the term when the reader will need the exact name to act on it —
copy a token, find a file, debug a regression, search the codebase.
Skip it when it is decoration. If the same idea fits in plain language
without losing accuracy or making the sentence longer, use plain
language. This is the same test [`communication-style.mdc`](./communication-style.mdc)
uses for chat replies; it applies to written entries too.

### Length and shape

- **Most entries are 1–3 sentences.** Substantial changes (component
  rewritten, page redesigned, multi-system restructure) can run a few
  more, but if you are past one short paragraph you are narrating
  implementation, not the change.
- **Lead with what changed**, not the steps you took to change it.
- **File paths and function names are fine when they orient** — not
  required, not the point.
- **No line numbers** (`lines 102-107`). Files change; line numbers go
  stale immediately.
- **No internal phase terminology** (`Phase 13 restructure`,
  `RUN_ID nav-header-...`, "the proof-of-fix for X workflow"). The
  reader does not have that context.
- **No `?v=N` cache-bust enumeration.** One line per version covering
  all bumped query params is plenty; if nothing was bumped, omit the
  line entirely.
- **No merge-resolution narratives.** "Merged with main; both branches
  bumped to .5; resolved to .6." is a commit-message detail, not a
  changelog entry.
- **Exact tag names go in backticks** (`` `<select>` ``). The renderer
  escapes literal `<` / `>` in entry text so they show as text — but
  backticks render as `<code>` and read better.

If the change is genuinely big, write a one-line summary as the entry
and put the implementation detail in the per-component
`changelog.json`, the PR description, or the commit message. Those
artifacts have technical voice non-negotiable per
[`communication-style.mdc`](./communication-style.mdc) §"Where
technical voice is non-negotiable".

## Exceptions

- Do NOT create a site changelog entry for changes that ONLY affect files outside `uds-docs/` (e.g. editing Cursor rules)
